const e='---\ntitle: "Theme Admin Extensions"\ndescription: "How APayShop themes register and render custom admin extension pages."\n---\n\n# Theme Admin Extensions\n\nAPayShop now supports **theme-owned admin extension pages**. This mechanism allows each active storefront theme to provide its own backend workspace without replacing the core `/admin` shell.\n\n## Design Goal\n\nThe goal is not to let themes fully rewrite the admin dashboard. Instead, APayShop keeps the core admin system unified and lets themes register additional pages through a predictable extension boundary.\n\nThis means:\n\n- Core admin pages still live under `app/pages/admin/`\n- Authentication, layout, navigation shell and system workflows stay centralized\n- Themes can add their own backend pages under `/admin/extensions/*`\n\n## File Structure\n\nEach theme can register custom admin pages with the following structure:\n\n```text\napp/themes/[theme]/\n  theme.admin.json\n  admin/\n    pages/\n      theme-workspace.vue\n      content-studio.vue\n```\n\n### Manifest File\n\nThe manifest file is:\n\n```text\napp/themes/[theme]/theme.admin.json\n```\n\nIt declares which admin extension pages should be exposed for the current theme.\n\n### Component Directory\n\nThe actual Vue page components live in:\n\n```text\napp/themes/[theme]/admin/pages/\n```\n\n## Runtime Flow\n\nAt runtime, APayShop uses a shared extension registry to:\n\n1. Read the current `active_theme`\n2. Load that theme\'s `theme.admin.json`\n3. Match the registered route\n4. Resolve the Vue component from `admin/pages`\n5. Render it through the common admin extension route\n\nThe core loader is implemented in [useAdminExtensions.ts](file:///Users/coller/aihop/APayShop/app/composables/useAdminExtensions.ts).\n\n## Route Namespace\n\nTheme-owned admin pages are rendered through:\n\n```text\n/admin/extensions/*\n```\n\nThe common route entry is:\n\n[extensions route](file:///Users/coller/aihop/APayShop/app/pages/admin/extensions/%5B...slug%5D.vue)\n\nThis route acts as a stable container for all theme extension pages.\n\n## Sidebar and Search Integration\n\nRegistered extension pages are automatically injected into:\n\n- The default admin sidebar\n- The mobile admin menu\n- The admin route search palette\n\nRelevant files:\n\n- [default.vue](file:///Users/coller/aihop/APayShop/app/themes/default/layouts/default.vue)\n- [RouteSearch.vue](file:///Users/coller/aihop/APayShop/app/components/RouteSearch.vue)\n\nThis avoids scattering hardcoded links across multiple places whenever a theme adds a new backend page.\n\n## Example Manifest\n\n```json\n{\n  "name": "Extensions",\n  "pages": [\n    {\n      "key": "theme-workspace",\n      "title": "Theme Workspace",\n      "description": "Manage storefront-specific operator workflows.",\n      "route": "/admin/extensions/theme-workspace",\n      "component": "theme-workspace.vue",\n      "icon": "ph:stack",\n      "order": 10\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n## Current Principles\n\nWhen extending the admin system through themes, follow these rules:\n\n- Keep core admin pages in `app/pages/admin/`\n- Put theme-specific admin pages inside the theme directory\n- Register extension entries through `theme.admin.json`\n- Reuse the shared `/admin/extensions/*` namespace\n- Do not make a theme take over the entire admin layout\n\n## Why This Matters\n\nThis design keeps APayShop:\n\n- Easier to maintain\n- Safer to upgrade\n- Cleaner for multi-theme projects\n- More understandable for AI-assisted development\n\nIn short, themes can now **extend** the admin dashboard, but the system still **owns** the admin shell.\n';export{e as default};
